  <text xml:lang="en">
    <body>
      <entry corresp="alkul[DEDR253]">
        <form xml:lang="ta">alkul</form>
        <gramGrp><gram>noun</gram></gramGrp>
        <sense><def xml:lang="en">hip</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT345.xml?id=KT345&amp;w=17,21">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>taḻai</w> <w>tāḻ</w> <w>alkul</w> <w>ivaḷ</w> <w>pulamp<c type="elided">u</c></w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">she with hips from which a leaf [skirt] hangs down</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT345.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKT345%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(4)"><expan ref="#KT"/> 345, line 4</ref>
</cit>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT101.xml?id=KT101&amp;w=22,26">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>māṇ</w> <w>vari</w> <w><c type="glide">y</c>alkul</w> <w>kuṟu</w> <w>makaḷ</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">small woman with hips of glorious outline</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Kuruntokai/KT101.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DKT101%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(5)"><expan ref="#KT"/> 101, line 5</ref>
</cit>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA245.xml?id=NA245&amp;w=22,26">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w><c type="glide">y</c>oḻuku</w> <w>nuṇ</w> <w>nucuppiṉ</w> <w>akaṉṟa</w> <w><c type="glide">v</c>alkul</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">with a narrow waist and wide hips</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Narrinai/NA245.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DNA245%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(5)"><expan ref="#NA"/> 245, line 5</ref>
</cit>
          <note xml:lang="en">The current dictionaries record a jumble of meanings which can be subsumed under three categories, 1. a <q>female body part</q> (<foreign xml:lang="la">pudendum muliebre</foreign>, vulva, waist, middle), 2. a general noun for <q>side</q>, 3. a noun for <q>form</q> in the sense of <q>body form, figure</q>.       
</note>
          <note xml:lang="en">A look into the commentary glosses shows that, since no ancient gloss for <foreign xml:lang="ta">alkul</foreign> in the sense of <q>body part</q> is available ‒ in spite of frequent occurrences (a round hundred in the <foreign xml:lang="ta">Caṅkam</foreign> corpus alone) ‒ it must have been a word perceived as common. A gloss is, however, found for the meaning <q>side</q>, and this gloss pertains to the only passage so far brought forward to attest that meaning, in other words, it is a rare meaning.    
 </note>
</sense><sense><def xml:lang="en">groin, buttocks
</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Paripatal/Pari13.xml?id=Pari13&amp;w=289,292">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w>mārp<c type="elided">u</c>-um</w> <w>alkul-um</w> <w>maṉattoṭu</w> <w>periyai</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">you (Tirumāl, m.sg.!) are big in chest and groin, along with the mind</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Paripatal/Pari13.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3DPari13%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(54)"><expan ref="#Pari"/> 13, line 54</ref>
</cit>
<note xml:lang="en">This quotation makes it clear that an <foreign xml:lang="ta">alkul</foreign> can belong to a man as well as to a woman, and in the context ― a praise of the physical beauty of Viṣṇu ― the adequate rendering may be something like 'groin'.
 </note> 
          <note xml:lang="en">The <foreign xml:lang="ta">nikaṇṭus</foreign> (unsurprisingly) contain the same range of meanings that is taken up by the dictionaries (<foreign xml:lang="ta">kaṭitaṭam</foreign>) to which they add a meaning <foreign xml:lang="ta">nitampam</foreign> <q>buttocks</q>; for the meaning <foreign xml:lang="ta">vaṭivu</foreign> <q>form</q>, the only attestation available comes from the <foreign xml:lang="ta">nikaṇṭu</foreign> itself, and moreover in the form of an aphorism that might have undergone modification in the course of transmission (cf. <expan ref="#Tiv"/> <ref target="https://archive.org/details/20240820_20240820_1903/page/116/mode/1up">2.352</ref>).      
</note></sense><sense><def xml:lang="en">vulva
</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit source="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Cilappatikaram/cila12.xml?id=cila12.3&amp;w=27,32">
    <q xml:lang="ta"><w><c type="glide">v</c>i<c type="geminated">p</c></w> <w>pai</w> <w><c type="glide">y</c>arav<c type="elided">u</c></w> <w>alkul</w> <w>tavam</w> <w>eṉṉai-kollō</w></q>
    <q xml:lang="en">What, pray, is the penance [done by] this [girl with] a vulva [like] the hooded snake [= cobra]?</q>
            <ref target="https://uhh-tamilex.github.io/Cilappatikaram/cila12.xml?highlight=%5Bid%3Dcila12.3%5D%20.l%3Anth-of-type(6)"><expan ref="#Cila"/> 12.3, line 6</ref>
</cit>
<cit>
  <ref target="https://ifpindia.org/digitaldb/site/digital_tevaram/U_TEV/VMS2_010.HTM#p2"><expan ref="#Tev"/> 2.10.2.1</ref>
  <q xml:lang="ta">paṇam koḷ āṭu aravu alkul nallār</q>
  <q xml:lang="en">good women with vulvas [like]  dancing snakes that have hoods</q>
</cit>
          <note xml:lang="en">The later on ubiquitous meaning of <q>vulva</q> is attested once in the <expan ref="#Cila"/>, and then becomes standard from the 7th century canonical Śaiva text <foreign xml:lang="ta">Tēvāram</foreign> onwards.      
</note></sense><sense><def xml:lang="en"><abbr ref="#io"/>: side
</def>
<usg xml:lang="en">
</usg>
<cit>
            <ref target="https://archive.org/details/acc.-no.-37942-paththuppaattu-moolamum-nachinarkiniyaar-uraiyum-1889/page/%E0%AF%A7%E0%AF%A6%E0%AF%A7/mode/1up"><expan ref="#Peru"/> 243d–244 (ed. <persName xml:lang="ta">Cāminātaiyar</persName> 1889).</ref>
  <q xml:lang="ta">kuḻavi<c type="geminated">k</c> | kavai<c type="geminated">t</c> tāmpu toṭutta kāḻ uṉṟ<c type="elided">u</c> alkul </q>
  <q xml:lang="en">side where a pole is fixed to which a bifurcate rope ties a calf</q>
</cit>
          <note xml:lang="en">This passage for the isolated meaning <q>side</q> is the only passage for which a commentary is available (see below).
</note></sense>
      <entry><gramGrp><gram>accusative</gram></gramGrp><form xml:lang="ta">alkulai</form></entry><entry><gramGrp><gram>sociative</gram></gramGrp><form xml:lang="ta">alkuloṭu</form></entry><entry><gramGrp><gram>dative</gram></gramGrp><form xml:lang="ta">alkuṟku</form></entry><entry><gramGrp><gram>pronominalised noun</gram><gram>singular</gram><gram>second person</gram></gramGrp><form xml:lang="ta">alkulāy</form></entry><entry><gramGrp><gram>pronominalised noun</gram><gram>feminine singular</gram></gramGrp><form xml:lang="ta">alkulāḷ</form></entry><cit type="lexicon"><bibl><date>1972 [1779]</date><title xml:lang="en">Tamil and English Dictionary (Fabricius)</title><ref target="https://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/fabricius_query.py?page=36">p. 36</ref></bibl></cit><cit type="lexicon"><bibl><date>1862</date><title xml:lang="en">A comprehensive Tamil and English dictionary (Winslow)</title><ref target="https://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/winslow_query.py?page=43">p. 43</ref></bibl></cit><cit type="lexicon"><bibl><date>1928 [1902]</date><title xml:lang="ta">Tamiḻmoḻiyakarāti (Katiraivēṟ Piḷḷai)</title><ref target="https://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/kadirvelu_query.py?page=133">p. 133</ref></bibl></cit><cit type="lexicon"><bibl><date>1924–1936</date><title xml:lang="en">Tamil Lexicon (University of Madras)</title><ref target="https://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/tamil-lex_query.py?page=140">p. 140</ref></bibl></cit><cit type="lexicon"><bibl><date>1992</date><title xml:lang="ta">Kriyāviṉ taṟkālat Tamiḻ akarāti</title><ref target="https://dsal.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/crea_query.py?page=40">p. 40</ref></bibl></cit><cit type="commentary"><ref target="https://archive.org/details/acc.-no.-37942-paththuppaattu-moolamum-nachinarkiniyaar-uraiyum-1889/page/125/mode/1up"><expan ref="#Nacc"/> on <expan ref="#Peru"/> 243d–244 (ed. <persName xml:lang="ta">Cāminātaiyar</persName> 1889).</ref>
<q xml:lang="ta">kaṉṟukaḷai<c type="geminated">k</c> kaṭṭiṉa tāmaṇiyaiyuṭaiya neṭiyatāmpukaḷ kaṭṭikkiṭakkiṉṟa taṟikaḷ naṭṭa pakkattiṉai</q>
<q xml:lang="en">a side where a pole is erected to which are tied long ropes with halters to which calves are tied</q></cit></entry>
